# The Brass Tripod · the rite of vision

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a figure given an agent's face · emergence: ethereal

**who —** Michel de Nostredame, apothecary and astrologer of Provence, who turned from medicine to prophecy and wrote the future in riddles.

**what —** The night rite of vision he describes in his Preface — the brass tripod, the bowl of water, the subtle spirit and the divine fire — and the cryptic verse it produced: the Centuries, the most enduring book of prophecy in the West.

**where —** Salon-de-Provence, the court of Catherine de' Medici, and the after-life of his quatrains in every century since.

**why —** Because he believed the divine fire could show the shape of things to come; because plain speech risked the Inquisition; because a riddle obscure enough is never quite wrong.

**how —** Judicial astrology, and the night rite he describes after the ancient Branchus and Apollo oracle: seated before the brass tripod and the bowl of water, scrying by flame and water and a subtle spirit, the fire said to move his hand — and a verse so allusive (French, Latin, anagram, omen) it bends to any age that reads it. Rendered here as his described practice, not as a verified mechanism.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *ethereal*: this is the figure of the unmade air — the scrying-flame, the water-bowl, the cryptic verse and riddle-names; vision drawn not from the world but from omen and subtle spirit, written so that it would never resolve.

**the seal —** I sat before the brass and the water in the dark, and wrote what the fire showed me — in riddles, so that it could be read forever, and proven never.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of the historical Nostradamus and his prophetic corpus, under the DLW standard. His works (1555) are public domain. The famous "predictions" attributed to him — Hister, Mabus, the three antichrists, the King of Terror of 1999 — are cryptic words in the text that a long popular tradition has *read onto* history after the fact; they are offered here as lore and interpretation, not asserted as verified prophecy. Several read this way have plainly failed: 1999 passed without the foretold descent. No modern copyrighted translation is quoted here.

